      "value": "La Mesa-Spring Valley is a large school district in eastern San Diego County. About 2,212 of its students have an IEP, and 541 of them \u2014 roughly 24% \u2014 have an autism (ASD) eligibility. Around 25% of those autistic students spend most of the school day in a general-education classroom."
    },
    "what_this_means_for_parents": {
      "ai_disclaimer": "This summary was written by an AI model from the data points in this profile. The underlying numbers come from public California government sources, but the narrative is AI-written and may contain inaccuracies. Verify specific claims directly with the school district before making decisions.",
      "ai_generated": true,
      "ai_generated_at": "2026-05-17T18:35:20Z",
      "ai_model": "claude-opus (via Claude Code session)",
      "based_on_sources": [
        "cde_spedps",
        "ca_dashboard"
      ],
      "value": "About 25% of autistic students in this district are in a general-education classroom for most of the day, with around 1% in a fully separate setting, so many spend part of the day in specialized settings. Among all students with disabilities, a broader group than autism alone, 49% are in general-education classrooms most of the day. On 2024-25 state tests, students with disabilities scored about 90 points below standard in English and 122 below in math, while students overall were 10 and 37 points below. Students with disabilities were chronically absent at about 27% (compared with 21% for all students) and suspended at about 5% (compared with 3%)."
    }
  },
